======================================================================
PROVING e_j = C(m+j, 2j) FOR INTERVAL Q-POLYNOMIAL
======================================================================

--- PART 1: THE POLYNOMIAL P_m(t) ---
P_m(t) = sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^j C(m+j,2j) t^{m-j}
This is the REVERSE of the Catalan triangle polynomial!

  P_2(t) = (1)*t^2 + (-3)*t^1 + (1)*t^0
  P_3(t) = (1)*t^3 + (-6)*t^2 + (5)*t^1 + (-1)*t^0
  P_5(t) = (1)*t^5 + (-15)*t^4 + (35)*t^3 + (-28)*t^2 + (9)*t^1 + (-1)*t^0
  P_6(t) = (1)*t^6 + (-21)*t^5 + (70)*t^4 + (-84)*t^3 + (45)*t^2 + (-11)*t^1 + (1)*t^0
  P_8(t) = (1)*t^8 + (-36)*t^7 + (210)*t^6 + (-462)*t^5 + (495)*t^4 + (-286)*t^3 + (91)*t^2 + (-15)*t^1 + (1)*t^0

--- PART 2: CHEBYSHEV CONNECTION ---
The Chebyshev U polynomial of the SECOND kind:
  U_n(x) = sin((n+1)*theta) / sin(theta) where x = cos(theta)

Consider R_m(t) = t^m * P_m(1/t) (reversed polynomial):
  R_m(t) = sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^j C(m+j,2j) t^j

Is R_m(t) related to Chebyshev?
U_{2m}(x) evaluated at x = (1-2t)/2 = 1/2 - t?
  m=3, P_3(Q_1) = 5.684342e-14
