--- PART 6: Q_k AS CHEBYSHEV RATIO ---
Q_k = (1 - cos((m+1)*alpha)) / (1 - cos(alpha))
    = (1 - T_{m+1}(cos(alpha))) / (1 - cos(alpha))
    = U_m(cos(alpha)) * (1 - cos(alpha)) ... no

Actually: 1 - cos(n*theta) = 2*sin^2(n*theta/2)
And: sin^2(n*theta/2) = n^2 * prod_{j=1}^{n-1} sin^2(theta/2 - j*pi/n)?
Better: use the identity
  (1 - T_n(x)) / (1 - x) = U_{n-1}(x) + U_{n-2}(x) + ... + U_0(x)
  = sum_{k=0}^{n-1} U_k(x)
This is a KNOWN identity for Chebyshev polynomials.

So Q_k = (1 - T_{m+1}(cos(alpha))) / (1 - cos(alpha))
       = U_m(cos(alpha)) + U_{m-1}(cos(alpha)) + ... + U_0(cos(alpha))
       = sum_{j=0}^m U_j(cos(alpha))
where alpha = 2*pi*k/p.

